Class Test

  • Object
    • Test

  • public class Test
extends Object

    A comprehensive test for Multiset's functionality and performance.

    For each of the four provided implementations (CoarseGrainedMultiset, FineGrainedMultiset, LazyMultiset, LockFreeMultiset) the class tests all major methods (both overloads of add, both overloads of remove, count, contains, removeAll). First, every method is tested with a thread barrier in order to check their correctness. Then, the barrier is removed and their performances (measured as a function of time) are printed and collected. The whole process is repeated using 1, 10, 100 and 1000 threads.

    Upon successful completion of all tasks, the test creates a file (named log.txt) with detailed results on the completion times of the various operations, together with an indication of which kind of implementation provides the fastest results for that particular operation and how much an implementation "scales" up when the number of threads increases.

    Author:
    Orlando Leombruni
    See Also:
    AddTest, RemoveAllTest, RemoveCountContainsTest

      • getBest

        public static String getBest(double[] arr)
        Compares the performance of the various implementations (with regards to a single operation) and produces a string which indicates the name of the implementation which provides the best result.
        Parameters:
        arr - An array of 4 time measurements (in seconds) for the completion of a multiset operation according to 4 different implementations, in this order: coarse-grained, fine-grained, lazy, lock-free.
        Returns:
        A string containing the name of the implementation which provided the best result.

      • getScalability

        public static String getScalability(double a,
                                    double b,
                                    double c,
                                    double d)
        An utility function to compute the scalability of an implementation of Multiset (with regards to a specific operation) given the time needed to complete a task with 1, 10, 100 and 1000 threads.
        Parameters:
        a - The time measurement (in seconds) for the completion of the operation using 1 thread.
        b - The time measurement (in seconds) for the completion of the operation using 10 threads.
        c - The time measurement (in seconds) for the completion of the operation using 100 threads.
        d - The time measurement (in seconds) for the completion of the operation using 1000 threads.
        Returns:
        A string containing the scalability factors with respect to the sequential (1 thread) case.
